File: platform/browser-extension/src/side-panel/App.tsx, lines 134-147.

The ws:message listener is a fallback for when the side panel doesn't receive sp:serverMessage (e.g., opened as extension page rather than via chrome.sidePanel.open). Currently it calls handleNotification(wsData) for all methods, but the background ALSO forwards tab.stateChanged, tool.invocationStart, tool.invocationEnd, and plugins.changed via sp:serverMessage (see SIDE_PANEL_METHODS in message-router.ts). This means those notifications are processed twice.

The fix: Change the ws:message handler (lines 134-147) to only handle sync.full. Remove the `else if (wsData)` branch that calls handleNotification. The ws:message path exists because sync.full is NOT forwarded to the side panel (it's not in SIDE_PANEL_METHODS), so the side panel needs the ws:message fallback only for that.

Current code:
```
if (message.type === 'ws:message') {
  const wsData = message.data as Record<string, unknown> | undefined;
  if (wsData?.method === 'sync.full') {
    loadPluginsRef.current();
  } else if (wsData) {
    handleNotification(wsData);
  }
  return false;
}
```

Fix:
```
if (message.type === 'ws:message') {
  const wsData = message.data as Record<string, unknown> | undefined;
  if (wsData?.method === 'sync.full') {
    loadPluginsRef.current();
  }
  return false;
}
```

This is safe because all notification methods the side panel needs (tab.stateChanged, tool.invocationStart/End, plugins.changed) are in SIDE_PANEL_METHODS and get forwarded via sp:serverMessage.

File: platform/browser-extension/src/side-panel/App.tsx, lines 117-121 and 134-139.

The problem: When the MCP server sends sync.full, two independent paths trigger loadPlugins():
1. ws:message handler (line 136) sees sync.full -> loadPlugins()
2. background's handleSyncFull sends plugins.changed notification -> arrives as sp:serverMessage at line 118 -> loadPlugins()

Both call fetchConfigState() which sends config.getState to the server.

The fix after US-001 removes the handleNotification call from ws:message but the sync.full path AND plugins.changed path both still call loadPlugins. The simplest dedup: add a timestamp guard to loadPlugins.

Approach: Wrap loadPlugins in a debounce. Use a ref to track the last call time. If called within 200ms of the previous call, skip. This is a common React pattern.

Current loadPlugins is defined with useCallback([], []). Modify it to check a ref:
```
const lastFetchRef = useRef(0);
const loadPlugins = useCallback(() => {
  const now = Date.now();
  if (now - lastFetchRef.current < 200) return;
  lastFetchRef.current = now;
  fetchConfigState()
    .then(result => { ... })
    .catch(() => {});
}, []);
```

This ensures plugins.changed from plugin.update (which doesn't overlap with sync.full timing) still triggers a fetch, while the rapid sync.full + plugins.changed double-fire is deduped.

Also remove the loadPluginsRef indirection (see US-003) since loadPlugins is already stable.

File: platform/browser-extension/src/side-panel/App.tsx, lines 39-42.

Current code:
```
const loadPluginsRef = useRef(loadPlugins);
useEffect(() => {
  loadPluginsRef.current = loadPlugins;
}, [loadPlugins]);
```

This ref indirection exists so 'the effect listener always calls the current version without needing loadPlugins in the dependency array'. But loadPlugins is wrapped in useCallback([], []) -- it has a stable identity that never changes. The ref adds complexity for zero benefit.

Remove the ref and its sync effect. In the main useEffect (line 44), add loadPlugins to the dependency array. Since loadPlugins never changes (stable useCallback), the effect won't re-run. Replace all loadPluginsRef.current() calls with loadPlugins():
- Line 48: loadPluginsRef.current() -> loadPlugins()
- Line 97: loadPluginsRef.current() -> loadPlugins()
- Line 119: loadPluginsRef.current() -> loadPlugins()
- Line 139: loadPluginsRef.current() -> loadPlugins()

This makes the code simpler and more idiomatic React.

File: platform/browser-extension/src/side-panel/components/PluginCard.tsx, lines 68-82.

Current rollback code (line 75-79):
```
void setAllToolsEnabled(plugin.name, newEnabled).catch(() => {
  setPlugins(prev =>
    prev.map(p =>
      p.name === plugin.name ? { ...p, tools: p.tools.map(t => ({ ...t, enabled: !newEnabled })) } : p,
    ),
  );
  showToggleError('Failed to toggle all tools');
});
```

The rollback sets ALL tools to `!newEnabled`, but if the pre-toggle state was mixed (some true, some false), this loses the original state.

Fix: Capture the original tools array before the optimistic update:
```
const handleToggleAll = (e: React.MouseEvent) => {
  e.stopPropagation();
  const newEnabled = !allEnabled;
  const originalTools = plugin.tools;
  setPlugins(prev =>
    prev.map(p => (p.name === plugin.name ? { ...p, tools: p.tools.map(t => ({ ...t, enabled: newEnabled })) } : p)),
  );
  void setAllToolsEnabled(plugin.name, newEnabled).catch(() => {
    setPlugins(prev =>
      prev.map(p =>
        p.name === plugin.name ? { ...p, tools: originalTools } : p,
      ),
    );
    showToggleError('Failed to toggle all tools');
  });
};
```

Note: `plugin.tools` is captured from the render-time props, which reflects the pre-toggle state because setPlugins hasn't committed yet at capture time. The captured `originalTools` array contains the exact per-tool states. On error, restore this exact snapshot.

Actually, since `plugin` comes from the current render props and `setPlugins` triggers a re-render, `plugin.tools` at the point of `handleToggleAll` invocation IS the pre-toggle state. Capturing it in a const before the optimistic setPlugins call is safe.
